data.content:
## .NET 8 Migration: `TimedExecutor`

### Key Breaking Changes

1. **`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** — removed entirely in .NET Core+
2. **`Thread.ResetAbort()` also unsupported** — no abort mechanism exists to reset
3. The entire abort-based timeout pattern must be replaced with **cooperative cancellation** via `CancellationToken`

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    /// <summary>
    /// Executes work with a timeout using cooperative cancellation.
    /// The work delegate must observe the CancellationToken to be
    /// truly cancellable — this is a fundamental design shift from
    /// Thread.Abort()'s preemptive model.
    /// </summary>
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            var task = Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);
            return task.GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
        {
            // Unwrap single-exception aggregates for cleaner caller experience
            throw ex.InnerExceptions[0];
        }
    }

    // Overload preserving the original signature for non-cancellable work.
    // ⚠️  WARNING: If 'work' ignores cancellation, this only stops WAITING — 
    // the work continues running in the background (fire-and-forget leak).
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
        var token = cts.Token;

        var task = Task.Run(work, token);

        try
        {
            // task.Wait(token) will throw when the timeout fires,
            // even if the task itself keeps running.
            task.Wait(token);
            return task.GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

### Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---|---|
| **No preemptive kill** | Unlike `Thread.Abort()`, cancellation is *cooperative*. If `work` never checks the token, it runs forever in the background. |
| **Thread pool starvation** | `Task.Run` uses the thread pool. Long-blocking work can starve it. Use `Task.Factory.StartNew(..., TaskCreationOptions.LongRunning)` if needed. |
| **Deadlock with `.GetResult()`** | Safe here (no `SynchronizationContext` in console/.NET 8 APIs), but in UI/ASP.NET contexts prefer `async Task<T>` end-to-end. |
| **Resource leaks** | `Thread.Abort()` would (unsafely) tear down work mid-stream. Cooperative cancellation won't — your work must handle cleanup via `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` or `token.Register(...)`. |

### Caller Migration

```csharp
// BEFORE (.NET Framework)
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    () => SlowDatabaseCall(),
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));

// AFTER (.NET 8) — pass token into the work
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    ct => SlowDatabaseCall(ct),   // propagate token to I/O APIs
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

**Bottom line:** `Thread.Abort()` was always unsafe (corrupted state, leaked locks). .NET 8 forces the correct pattern — propagate `CancellationToken` into your I/O and loop-based work so it can exit cleanly.
